Process called "setup_standard_environment" that takes ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Set up standard Bash environment variables

    @Reasoning:
    Bash has standard environment variables that affect its behavior
    and are commonly used in scripts. These should be available
    for semantic analysis.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Standard shell variables
    Call add_standard_variable with ctx and "BASH" and "/bin/bash"
    Call add_standard_variable with ctx and "BASH_VERSION" and "5.0"
    Call add_standard_variable with ctx and "HOME" and "/home/user"
    Call add_standard_variable with ctx and "PATH" and "/usr/local/bin:/usr/bin:/bin"
    Call add_standard_variable with ctx and "PWD" and "/current/directory"
    Call add_standard_variable with ctx and "OLDPWD" and "/previous/directory"
    Call add_standard_variable with ctx and "USER" and "user"
    Call add_standard_variable with ctx and "SHELL" and "/bin/bash"
    Call add_standard_variable with ctx and "TERM" and "xterm"
    Call add_standard_variable with ctx and "LANG" and "en_US.UTF-8"
    Call add_standard_variable with ctx and "LC_ALL" and "C"

    Note: Special parameters
    Call add_special_parameter with ctx and "$" and "shell PID"
    Call add_special_parameter with ctx and "?" and "last exit status"
    Call add_special_parameter with ctx and "!" and "background job PID"
    Call add_special_parameter with ctx and "#" and "argument count"
    Call add_special_parameter with ctx and "*" and "all arguments"
    Call add_special_parameter with ctx and "@" and "all arguments (array)"
    Call add_special_parameter with ctx and "0" and "script name"

    Note: Set default shell options
    Call set_shell_option with ctx and "errexit" and false
    Call set_shell_option with ctx and "nounset" and false
    Call set_shell_option with ctx and "pipefail" and false
    Call set_shell_option with ctx and "xtrace" and false
    Call set_shell_option with ctx and "verbose" and false
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST NODE ANALYSIS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "analyze_bash_node" that takes node as HIRNode, ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze any Bash AST node based on its type

    Match node.type:
        When "Script":
            Call analyze_bash_script with node and ctx
        When "Command":
            Call analyze_bash_command with node and ctx
        When "SimpleCommand":
            Call analyze_bash_simple_command with node and ctx
        When "Pipeline":
            Call analyze_bash_pipeline with node and ctx
        When "List":
            Call analyze_bash_list with node and ctx
        When "Assignment":
            Call analyze_bash_assignment with node and ctx
        When "FunctionDefinition":
            Call analyze_bash_function_definition with node and ctx
        When "IfStatement":
            Call analyze_bash_if_statement with node and ctx
        When "ForLoop":
            Call analyze_bash_for_loop with node and ctx
        When "WhileLoop":
            Call analyze_bash_while_loop with node and ctx
        When "UntilLoop":
            Call analyze_bash_until_loop with node and ctx
        When "CaseStatement":
            Call analyze_bash_case_statement with node and ctx
        When "CompoundCommand":
            Call analyze_bash_compound_command with node and ctx
        When "Subshell":
            Call analyze_bash_subshell with node and ctx
        When "CommandSubstitution":
            Call analyze_bash_command_substitution with node and ctx
        When "ProcessSubstitution":
            Call analyze_bash_process_substitution with node and ctx
        When "ArithmeticExpansion":
            Call analyze_bash_arithmetic_expansion with node and ctx
        When "ParameterExpansion":
            Call analyze_bash_parameter_expansion with node and ctx
        When "Redirection":
            Call analyze_bash_redirection with node and ctx
        When "HereDocument":
            Call analyze_bash_here_document with node and ctx
        When "WordExpansion":
            Call analyze_bash_word_expansion with node and ctx
        When "PatternMatching":
            Call analyze_bash_pattern_matching with node and ctx
        When "ArrayAccess":
            Call analyze_bash_array_access with node and ctx
        Otherwise:
            Call analyze_generic_bash_node with node and ctx
    End Match
End Process

Process called "analyze_bash_script" that takes node as HIRNode, ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze Bash script (top-level)

    Let shebang be node.shebang
    Let statements be node.statements

    Note: Validate shebang if present
    If shebang is not null:
        Call validate_shebang with shebang and ctx
    End If

    Note: Analyze all statements
    For Each statement in statements:
        Call analyze_bash_node with statement and ctx
    End For
End Process

Process called "analyze_bash_simple_command" that takes node as HIRNode, ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze simple Bash command

    @Reasoning:
    Simple commands are the core of Bash execution. They require checking
    command existence, argument validation, variable expansion, and
    redirection handling.
    @End Reasoning

    Let command_name be node.command_name
    Let arguments be node.arguments
    Let redirections be node.redirections
    Let assignments be node.assignments

    Note: Process variable assignments before command
    If assignments is not null:
        For Each assignment in assignments:
            Call analyze_bash_assignment with assignment and ctx
        End For
    End If

    Note: Resolve and validate command
    Let command_info be resolve_bash_command with command_name and ctx
    If command_info is null:
        Let error be "Command not found: " joined with command_name
        Add error to end of ctx.error_list
        Return
    End If

    Note: Validate command arguments
    Call validate_command_arguments with command_info and arguments and ctx

    Note: Analyze arguments for expansions
    If arguments is not null:
        For Each arg in arguments:
            Call analyze_bash_word_expansion with arg and ctx
        End For
    End If

    Note: Analyze redirections
    If redirections is not null:
        For Each redirection in redirections:
            Call analyze_bash_redirection with redirection and ctx
        End For
    End If
End Process

Process called "analyze_bash_assignment" that takes node as HIRNode, ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze Bash variable assignment

    @Reasoning:
    Bash assignments can create variables, arrays, or modify existing ones.
    They need proper scoping rules and type checking for arrays vs scalars.
    @End Reasoning

    Let var_name be node.variable_name
    Let value be node.value
    Let is_array_assignment be node.is_array_assignment
    Let array_index be node.array_index
    Let assignment_operator be node.assignment_operator

    Note: Check if variable is readonly
    If is_readonly_variable with var_name and ctx:
        Let error be "Cannot assign to readonly variable: " joined with var_name
        Add error to end of ctx.error_list
        Return
    End If

    Note: Analyze value expression
    Call analyze_bash_word_expansion with value and ctx

    Note: Handle different assignment types
    Match assignment_operator:
        When "=":
            Call handle_simple_assignment with var_name and value and ctx
        When "+=":
            Call handle_append_assignment with var_name and value and ctx
        When "array_assign":
            Call handle_array_assignment with var_name and array_index and value and ctx
        Otherwise:
            Set error to "Unknown assignment operator: " joined with assignment_operator
            Add error to end of ctx.error_list
    End Match
End Process

Process called "analyze_bash_function_definition" that takes node as HIRNode, ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze Bash function definition

    @Reasoning:
    Bash functions create new scopes, can shadow variables and commands,
    and have special parameter handling rules that need validation.
    @End Reasoning

    Let func_name be node.function_name
    Let body be node.body

    Note: Check if function name conflicts with built-ins
    If is_builtin_command with func_name and ctx:
        Let warning be "Function '" joined with func_name joined with "' shadows built-in command"
        Add warning to end of ctx.warning_list
    End If

    Note: Create function scope
    Let func_env be create_function_environment with ctx.current_environment and func_name

    Note: Create function object
    Let bash_function be a value of type BashFunction with
        name as func_name,
        body as body,
        local_variables as a list containing nothing,
        is_exported as false,
        source_location as node.source_location

    Note: Set function context and analyze body
    Let old_env be ctx.current_environment
    Let old_func be ctx.current_function
    Set ctx.current_environment to func_env
    Set ctx.current_function to func_name

    Call analyze_bash_node with body and ctx

    Note: Restore context
    Set ctx.current_environment to old_env
    Set ctx.current_function to old_func

    Note: Register function
    Set ctx.function_definitions at key func_name to bash_function
End Process

Process called "analyze_bash_pipeline" that takes node as HIRNode, ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze Bash pipeline

    @Reasoning:
    Pipelines connect commands through stdin/stdout and can affect
    exit status handling. Each command in the pipeline runs in
    a separate process.
    @End Reasoning

    Let commands be node.commands
    Let is_background be node.is_background

    Note: Analyze each command in pipeline
    For Each command in commands:
        Call analyze_bash_node with command and ctx
    End For

    Note: Check for pipeline-specific issues
    If length of commands is greater than 1:
        Note: Validate that first command produces output
        Call validate_pipeline_compatibility with commands and ctx
    End If

    Note: Handle background execution
    If is_background:
        If not ctx.job_control_enabled:
            Let warning be "Background jobs may not work without job control"
            Add warning to end of ctx.warning_list
        End If
    End If
End Process

Process called "analyze_bash_parameter_expansion" that takes node as HIRNode, ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze Bash parameter expansion

    @Reasoning:
    Parameter expansions can reference variables, perform substitutions,
    and modify values. They need validation for variable existence
    and proper syntax.
    @End Reasoning

    Let var_name be node.variable_name
    Let expansion_type be node.expansion_type
    Let modifier be node.modifier
    Let pattern be node.pattern
    Let replacement be node.replacement

    Note: Check if variable exists
    Let variable be lookup_bash_variable with var_name and ctx
    If variable is null and expansion_type is not equal to "default":
        Let warning be "Variable '" joined with var_name joined with "' may be unset"
        Add warning to end of ctx.warning_list
    End If

    Note: Validate expansion type and modifiers
    Match expansion_type:
        When "simple":
            Note: Basic variable reference
        When "default":
            Call validate_default_expansion with var_name and modifier and ctx
        When "assign":
            Call validate_assign_expansion with var_name and modifier and ctx
        When "substring":
            Call validate_substring_expansion with var_name and pattern and ctx
        When "replace":
            Call validate_replace_expansion with var_name and pattern and replacement and ctx
        When "length":
            Call validate_length_expansion with var_name and ctx
        When "keys":
            Call validate_keys_expansion with var_name and ctx
        Otherwise:
            Let error be "Unknown parameter expansion type: " joined with expansion_type
            Add error to end of ctx.error_list
    End Match
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HELPER FUNCTIONS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "resolve_bash_command" that takes command_name as String, ctx as BashSemanticContext returns BashCommand OR null:
    Note: Resolve command name to command information

    @Reasoning:
    Bash command resolution follows a specific order: aliases, functions,
    built-ins, and then PATH search. This needs to be accurately modeled
    for proper semantic analysis.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Check aliases first
    If ctx.alias_definitions contains key command_name:
        Let alias_target be ctx.alias_definitions at key command_name
        Return create_alias_command with command_name and alias_target
    End If

    Note: Check functions
    If ctx.function_definitions contains key command_name:
        Return create_function_command with command_name
    End If

    Note: Check built-ins
    If is_builtin_command with command_name and ctx:
        Return lookup_builtin_command with command_name and ctx
    End If

    Note: Check external commands in PATH
    Let external_cmd be search_path_for_command with command_name and ctx
    If external_cmd is not null:
        Return external_cmd
    End If

    Return null
End Process

Process called "lookup_bash_variable" that takes name as String, ctx as BashSemanticContext returns BashVariable OR null:
    Note: Look up variable in environment chain

    Let current_env be ctx.current_environment
    While current_env is not null:
        Note: Check local variables first
        If current_env.local_variables contains key name:
            Return current_env.local_variables at key name
        End If

        Note: Check regular variables
        If current_env.variables contains key name:
            Return current_env.variables at key name
        End If

        Set current_env to current_env.parent_env
    End While

    Return null
End Process

Process called "create_function_environment" that takes parent as BashEnvironment, func_name as String returns BashEnvironment:
    Note: Create new environment for function scope

    Return a value of type BashEnvironment with
        variables as a dictionary containing nothing,
        local_variables as a dictionary containing nothing,
        parent_env as parent,
        scope_type as "function",
        is_function_scope as true,
        is_subshell as false
End Process

Process called "validate_bash_semantics" that takes ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Perform final semantic validation

    @Reasoning:
    Final validation checks for Bash-specific issues such as undefined
    variables, command resolution problems, and shell option conflicts.
    @End Reasoning

    Call validate_variable_usage with ctx
    Call validate_function_usage with ctx
    Call validate_shell_options with ctx
    Call validate_redirection_usage with ctx
    Call validate_job_control_usage with ctx
End Process

Process called "validate_variable_usage" that takes ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Validate variable usage patterns

    Note: This  check for common variable usage issues
    Note: Implementation depends on tracking variable access patterns
End Process

Process called "validate_function_usage" that takes ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Validate function definitions and calls

    Note: Check for recursive functions, unused functions, etc.
End Process

Process called "validate_shell_options" that takes ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Validate shell option combinations

    Note: Check for conflicting shell options
End Process

Process called "validate_redirection_usage" that takes ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Validate file redirection usage

    Note: Check for file descriptor conflicts, permission issues
End Process

Process called "validate_job_control_usage" that takes ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Validate job control operations

    Note: Check job control is enabled when using bg/fg/jobs
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HELPER CREATION FUNCTIONS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "create_bash_command" that takes name as String, description as String, is_builtin as Boolean returns BashCommand:
    Return a value of type BashCommand with
        command_name as name,
        command_type as "builtin",
        is_builtin as is_builtin,
        is_function as false,
        is_alias as false,
        is_external as not is_builtin,
        expected_args as null,
        description as description
End Process

Process called "add_standard_variable" that takes ctx as BashSemanticContext, name as String, value as String returns Nothing:
    Let variable be a value of type BashVariable with
        name as name,
        value as value,
        type as "string",
        is_array as false,
        is_associative as false,
        is_exported as true,
        is_readonly as false,
        is_local as false,
        array_values as null,
        associative_values as null,
        first_assignment_line as 0,
        last_access_line as 0

    Set ctx.current_environment.variables at key name to variable
End Process

Process called "set_shell_option" that takes ctx as BashSemanticContext, option as String, value as Boolean returns Nothing:
    Set ctx.shell_options at key option to value
End Process

Process called "register_builtin_command" that takes cmd as BashCommand, ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Register builtin command for lookup
    Note: Implementation  store in builtin command registry
End Process

Note: Entry point for Bash semantic analysis
Process called "analyze_bash_semantic_tree" that takes ast as HIRNode returns BashSemanticContext:
    Return analyze_bash_semantics with ast
End Process